solution:
The area of the parallelogram generated by $\overrightarrow{OA}$ and $\overrightarrow{OB}$ is given by
\[\|\overrightarrow{OA} \times \overrightarrow{OB}\| = \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \right\| = \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ -10 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \right\| = 6 \sqrt{5}.\][asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,0);
B = (7,2);
C = (1,3);
D = B + C;

draw(A--B,Arrow(6));
draw(A--C,Arrow(6));
draw(B--C);
draw(B--D--C,dashed);

label("$O$", A, SW);
label("$A$", B, SE);
label("$B$", C, W);
[/asy]

Therefore, the area of triangle $OAB$ is $\boxed{3 \sqrt{5}}.$

Rewrite $x+y\leq 4$ as $y\leq 4-x$.  This inequality is satisfied by the points on and under the line $y=4-x$.  Sketching this line along with the $4\times 8$ rectangle determined by the inequalities $0\leq x\leq 8$ and $0\leq y\leq 4$, we find that the points satisfying $x+y\leq 4$ are those in the shaded triangle (see figure).  The  area of the triangle is $\frac{1}{2}(4)(4)=8$ square units, and the area of the rectangle is $(4)(8)=32$ square units, so the probability that a randomly selected point would fall in the shaded triangle is $\boxed{\frac{1}{4}}$.

[asy] import graph; size(200); defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));

dotfactor=4;

real f(real x) { return 4-x; }

pair A=(0,4), B=(8,4), C=(8,0), D=(0,0); pair[] dots={A,B,C,D};

fill(A--(4,0)--D--cycle,gray(0.7)); draw(A--B--C);

xaxis(xmin=-3,xmax=9,Ticks(" ",1.0, begin=false, end=false, NoZero, Size=3), Arrows(4), above=true);

yaxis(ymin=-1,ymax=5,Ticks(" ",1.0,begin=false, end=false, NoZero, Size=3), Arrows(4), above=true);

draw(graph(f,-0.8,4.5),Arrows(4)); label("$x+y=4$",(-2.2,5.2));[/asy]

Because $\triangle PQR$ is isosceles with $PQ=QR$, median $\overline{QM}$ is also an altitude:


[asy]
size(100);
pair P,Q,R,M,NN;
P = (0,0);
Q = (0.5,0.9);
R = (1,0);
NN = (0.5,0);
M = (Q+R)/2;
draw(rightanglemark(Q,NN,P,2.5));
draw(P--Q--R--P);
draw(Q--NN);
label("$P$",P,SW);
label("$R$",R,SE);
label("$Q$",Q,N);
label("$M$",NN,S);
[/asy]

We have $MP = PR/2 = 16$, so right triangle $PQM$ gives us  \begin{align*}
QM &= \sqrt{PQ^2 - PM^2}\\
&= \sqrt{34^2 - 16^2}\\
&= \sqrt{(34-16)(34+16)}\\
& = \boxed{30}.
\end{align*}  (We might also have recognized that $PM/PQ = 8/17$, so $QM/PQ = 15/17$.)

Since three of the roots of $p(x)$ are 1, 2, and 3, we can write
\[p(x) = (x - 1)(x - 2)(x - 3)(x - r).\]Then
\begin{align*}
p(0) + p(4) &= (-1)(-2)(-3)(-r) + (3)(2)(1)(4 - r) \\
&= 6r + 24 - 6r = \boxed{24}.
\end{align*}

Rearranging $x^2 - x - 1= 0$ gives $x^2 = x + 1$.  So, repeatedly substituting $x+1$ for $x^2$ gives us \begin{align*}
x^3 - 2x + 1 &= x(x^2)-2x + 1\\
&=x(x+1) - 2x + 1\\
&= x^2 + x -2x + 1\\
&= x^2 - x + 1\\
&= (x+1) - x + 1\\
&=\boxed{2}
\end{align*}

The rectangular region is 10 units by 8 units, resulting in an 8 by 6 rectangular region in the interior, which forms a 9-by-7 array of lattice points. That's $\boxed{63}$ points with integer coordinates, as shown in the figure. [asy]
import olympiad; size(150); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
add(grid(10,8));
draw((1,1)--(9,1)--(9,7)--(1,7)--cycle,linewidth(1.2));
[/asy] Note: We are counting points, not squares. It is a common mistake to count the interior squares, for 48, instead of interior lattice points, which gives the correct answer of 63.

Each pair of circles has at most two intersection points. There are $\binom{4}{2} = 6$ pairs of circles, so there are at most $6\times 2 = 12$ points of intersection. The following configuration shows that $\boxed{12}$ points of intersection are indeed possible:

[asy]
draw(Circle((0,0),2));
draw(Circle((1,1.3),2));
draw(Circle((-1,1.3),2));
draw(Circle((0,0.7),2));
[/asy]
